{{Infobox language | name = Chayahuita | nativename = Shawi | altname = Cahuapana | states = [[Peru]] | ethnicity = 21,400 (2011) | speakers = 14,000 | date = 2011 | ref = <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ethnologue.com/language/cbt|title=Shawi|work=Ethnologue|access-date=2018-07-23|language=en}}</ref> | familycolor = American | fam1 = [[Cahuapanan languages|Cahuapanan]] | iso3 = cbt | glotto = chay1248 | glottorefname = Chayahuita }}
'''Chayahuita''' is an endangered [[Amazonian languages|Amazonian language]] spoken by thousands of native Chayahuita people in the Amazon basin of north-central. Spoken along the banks of the Paranapura, Cahuapanas, Sillay, and Shanusi rivers, it is also known as Chayawita, Shawi, Chawi, Tshaahui, Chayhuita, Chayabita, Shayabit, Balsapuertino, Paranapura, and Cahuapa. There is a 1-5% literacy rate, compared with 5-15% for Spanish, and a dictionary since 1978. It can not be understood by [[Jebero language|Jebero]] speakers although there is some overlap in vocabulary, especially some [[Southern Quechua|Quechua]] terms.
== Phonology == There are 4 vowels: /a, i, ɨ, u/.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://linguistics.berkeley.edu/~saphon|title=SAPhon – South American Phonological Inventories|website=linguistics.berkeley.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-07-23}}</ref> {| class="wikitable" style="text-align:center" |+ Consonants ! ![[Bilabial consonant|Bilabial]] ![[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]] ![[Postalveolar consonant|Postalveolar]] ![[Palatal consonant|Palatal]] ![[Velar consonant|Velar]] ![[Glottal consonant|Glottal]] |- ![[Stop consonant|Stop]] |p |t | | |k |ʔ |- ![[Affricate consonant|Affricate]] | | |t͡ʃ | | | |- ![[Fricative consonant|Fricative]] |β |s |ʃ | | |h |- ![[Nasal consonant|Nasal]] |m |n | | | | |- ![[Approximant consonant|Approximant]] | | | |j |w | |- ![[Flap consonant|Flap]] | |ɾ | | | | |}
