{{Infobox language |name=Lamaholot |altname=Solorese |states=[[Indonesia]] |region=[[Flores]] and [[Solor]] |ethnicity=[[Lamaholot people]] |speakers=180,000 |date=2010 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Austronesian |fam2=[[Malayo-Polynesian languages|Malayo-Polynesian]] |fam3=[[Central–Eastern Malayo-Polynesian languages|Central–Eastern MP]] |fam4=[[Flores–Lembata languages|Flores–Lembata]] |fam5=Lamaholot |iso3=slp |glotto=lama1277 |glottorefname=Lamaholot }}
'''Lamaholot''', also known as '''Solor''' or '''Solorese''', is a [[Central Malayo-Polynesian languages|Central Malayo-Polynesian]] [[dialect cluster]] of [[Flores]], [[Indonesia]]. The varieties may not be all mutually intelligble; Keraf (1978) reports that there are 18 languages under the name.<ref>Keraf, Gorys. 1978. Komposisi. Ph.D. dissertation, Flores.</ref> The language shows evidence of a [[Papuan language|Papuan]] (non-Austronesian) substratum.
== References == {{reflist}}
{{Central Malayo-Polynesian languages}} {{Languages of Indonesia}}
[[Category:Flores-Lembata languages]] [[Category:Languages of Indonesia]] [[Category:Languages of the Maluku Islands]]
{{au-lang-stub}}

The term '''monkey's uncle''', most notably seen in the idiom "(well) I'll be a monkey's uncle", is used to express complete surprise, amazement or disbelief.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://idioms.thefreedictionary.com/I%27ll+be+a+monkey%27s+uncle! |title=I'll be a monkey's uncle! - Idioms |publisher=Idioms.thefreedictionary.com |date= |accessdate=2011-12-03}}</ref> It can also be used to acknowledge the impossibility of a situation, in the same way that "pigs might fly" is used. An example is if one says: "I may agree that if two plus two equals five, then I am a monkey's uncle". "I'll be a monkey's uncle" has been said to date from after 1925, the date of the widely publicized [[Scopes Trial]] in the United States, where the term first appears.<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MveDuTv3XF8C&pg=PA83&dq=%22Monkey%27s+uncle%22+darwin&hl=en&ei=5KPeTr_xCcWsiAeSsMSZBQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=9&ved=0CFgQ6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=%22Monkey%27s%20uncle%22%20darwin&f=false Now You Know Big Book of Answers 2 | title=Now You Know Big Book of Answers 2 | accessdate=December 7, 2011 | author=Lennox, Doug | pages=83}}</ref> The [[Oxford English Dictionary]]'s earliest example is the phrase ''If that's a joke I'm a monkey's uncle,'' from an [[Ohio]] newspaper on 8 February 1925.<ref>{{cite book|title=Oxford English Dictionary|url=http://www.oed.com/view/Entry/121265?rskey=63B7vd&result=1&isAdvanced=true#eid36273007|chapter=Monkey, noun: 9|quote=1925 Elyria (Ohio) Chronicle Telegram 8 Feb., If that's a joke I'm a monkey's uncle. | accessdate=2011-12-06}} ''Available online to subscribers, and also in print''</ref> It was originally a sarcastic remark made by [[creationist]]s.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://h2g2.com/dna/h2g2/plain/A3628 | title=A Monkey's Uncle | publisher=BBC | accessdate=December 7, 2011}}</ref> The notion "that [people] were descended from apes was considered blasphemous...by Darwin's contemporaries", and it was for this reason that the sarcastic phrase came into use.<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z2zbkWEXRCwC&pg=PA15&dq=%22Monkey%27s+uncle%22+darwin&hl=en&ei=EqTeTsabFqmXiAfk2MmxBQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=7&ved=0CEoQ6AEwBjgK#v=onepage&q=%22Monkey%27s%20uncle%22%20darwin&f=false | title=Science, theology, and consciousness: the search for unity | accessdate=December 7, 2011 | author=Arden, John Boghosian}}</ref>

[[Michael Quinion]] notes that the phrase ''Monkey's uncle'' occurs in a parody of [[Henry Wadsworth Longfellow|Longfellow]]'s ''[[The Song of Hiawatha]]'' which was reprinted in [[James Parton]]'s ''The Humorous Poetry of the English Language'', published in 1881, and observes ''This may be just an accident of invention, but the date fits''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Quinion|first=MIchael|title=Monkey's Uncle|url=http://www.worldwidewords.org/qa/qa-mon3.htm|work=World Wide Words|accessdate=6 December 2011|date=1 January 2005}}</ref> ''Monkey's Uncle'' is the name of a song by [[the Selecter]] on their album ''Reel to Real'' criticizing religious dogma that contradicts scientific evidence.

