{{Infobox language |name=Sengmai |altname= |states=[[India]] |region=[[Manipur]] |ethnicity= |speakers= extinct |date= |ref=<ref name="Matisoff2013">Matisoff, James A. 2013. [https://www.academia.edu/16300693/Re-examining_the_genetic_position_of_Jingpho_putting_flesh_on_the_bones_of_the_Jinghpho_Luish_Relationship Re-examining the genetic position of Jingpho: putting flesh on the bones of the Jingpho/Luish relationship]. ''Linguistics of the Tibeto-Burman Area'' 36(2). 1–106.</ref> |familycolor=Sino-Tibetan |fam2=[[Sal languages|Sal]] |fam3=[[Jingpho–Luish languages|Jingpho–Luish]] |fam4=[[Luish languages|Luish]] |iso3= |glotto=seng1275 |glottorefname=Sengmai }}
'''Sengmai''' is an extinct [[Sino-Tibetan languages|Sino-Tibetan language]] of [[Manipur]], [[India]]. It belongs to the [[Luish languages|Luish]] branch, and is most closely related to the [[Andro language]] of Manipur. Sengmai speakers have since shifted to [[Meithei language|Meithei]].
